<TITLE> European stocks edge higher in thin pre-Xmas trade </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PARIS, Dec 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European stocks eked out slim gains in early trade on Monday while volumes were expected to remain very thin in the shortened session ahead of the Christmas break. Banking shares found support from a report in the Financial Times that Saudi Arabia plans to establish a sovereign wealth fund that may exceed $900 billion, which would likely be the largest in the world. Barclays was up 1.2 percent and Royal Bank of Scotland advanced 1.4 percent. Banking shares, hammered over the past few months on worries over the troubled U.S. subprime mortgage market, recently got a boost when a number of major banks including Citigroup announced that sovereign wealth funds would inject capital. By 0820 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was up 0.14 percent at 1,509.22 points. Markets in Germany, Spain and many other countries were closed on Monday. Among standout gainers, shares in Capgemini jumped 7 percent after India's Hindustan Times newspaper quoting unnamed sources said that Wipro Ltd is expected to bid for Capgemini by the end of January in a deal valuing the French firm at up to $7 billion. A spokeswoman for Capgemini declined to comme
